awing upon a uniquely-detailed and rich content and framing analysis of television and press coverage, and on interviews with some of the journalists involved, Pockets of Resistance provides an authoritative assessment of how British news media reported the 2003 Iraq invasion and also of the theoretical implications of this case for our understanding of wartime media-state relations. Pockets of Resistance examines the successes and failures of British television news as it sought to attain independence under the difficult circumstances of war, and describes and explains the emergence of some surprisingly vociferous anti-war voices within a diverse national press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIraq War, 2003-2011xMass media and the war. 0aMass mediazGreat Britain. 0aTelevision broadcasting of newszGreat BritainxHistoryy21st century. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2021. 4aInternational Relations 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aAli Abbas.  aBritish news media.  aIraq invasion.  aJessica Lynch.  aanti-war movement.  acivilian casualties.  aelite-driven model.  aforeign policy.  ahumanitarian operations.  aindependent model.  amedia criticism.  amilitary casualties.  aoppositional coverage.  aoppositional model.  asupportive coverage.  awartime media performance.1 aGoddard, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGoddard, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParry, Katy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aParry, Katy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobinson, Piers, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Ph